IPv6 (Internet Protocol Version 6)
🎯 Objective

Learn what IPv6 is, why it was introduced, how it differs from IPv4, understand IPv6 address types, notation, advantages, and practice IPv6 commands on Linux.

📖 What is IPv6?

IPv6 (Internet Protocol Version 6) is the latest version of the Internet Protocol. It was developed to solve the IPv4 address exhaustion problem and to support the growing number of Internet-connected devices.

IPv6 uses 128-bit addresses, providing an enormous address space compared to IPv4's 32-bit addresses.

Why Was IPv6 Introduced?

IPv4 supports approximately:

4.3 Billion Addresses

With billions of smartphones, IoT devices, servers, and cloud resources, IPv4 addresses became insufficient.

IPv6 provides approximately:

340 Undecillion Addresses
(340,282,366,920,938,463,463,374,607,431,768,211,456)

This is enough to assign unique addresses to an extremely large number of devices.

IPv4 vs IPv6
Feature	IPv4	IPv6
Address Size	32-bit	128-bit
Address Format	Decimal	Hexadecimal
Example	192.168.1.10	2001:db8::10
Address Space	~4.3 Billion	~340 Undecillion
NAT Required	Often Yes	Usually No
Broadcast	Supported	Not Used
Security	Optional	Designed with IPsec support
Header	Variable (20–60 bytes)	Fixed (40 bytes)
IPv6 Address Format

Example:

2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334

It consists of eight groups of hexadecimal digits separated by colons.

IPv6 Address Compression

IPv6 allows you to shorten addresses.

Original:

2001:0db8:0000:0000:0000:0000:0000:0001

Compressed:

2001:db8::1

Rules:

Remove leading zeros in each group.
Replace one continuous sequence of all-zero groups with :: (only once per address).
Types of IPv6 Addresses
1. Unicast

Used for communication between one sender and one receiver.

Example:

2001:db8::10
2. Multicast

One sender communicates with multiple receivers.

Example prefix:

ff00::/8
3. Anycast

The same address is assigned to multiple devices. Traffic is delivered to the nearest device based on routing.

Special IPv6 Addresses
Address	Purpose
::1	Loopback (similar to 127.0.0.1)
::	Unspecified address
fe80::/10	Link-local addresses
2000::/3	Global unicast addresses
ff00::/8	Multicast addresses
IPv6 Communication
+-----------+                     +-----------+
| Computer A| ------------------> | Computer B|
|2001:db8::1|                     |2001:db8::2|
+-----------+                     +-----------+
Advantages of IPv6
Huge address space.
Better support for IoT.
Simpler header for efficient routing.
No broadcast traffic.
Built-in support for IPsec.
Better support for auto-configuration.
Disadvantages of IPv6
Older devices may not support it.
Transition from IPv4 requires planning.
Some legacy applications may need updates.
Linux Commands

Display IPv6 addresses:

ip -6 addr

Display IPv6 routing table:

ip -6 route

Ping using IPv6:

ping6 google.com

(If ping6 is unavailable on your system, use:)

ping -6 google.com

Show IPv6 sockets:

ss -6
